column16:
My overall physical traits phenotype is much closer to my father than my mother. Currently trying to sort out HLA inheritance. Received assistance with HLA*IMP software which imputed these haplotypes from my whole genome VCF file (with probabilities) -

allele1 allele2 probability

HLA-A* 03:01 26:01   100%  55%

HLA-B* 38:01 40:01   96%  86%

HLA-C* 12:03 07:02   100%  99%

HLA-DRB1* 04:04 09:01   82%  100%

HLA-DQA* 03:01 02:01    99%  76%

HLA-DQB1* 03:02 03:03   99%  98%

HLA-DPB* 04:04 09:01   82%  100%

The HLA*IMP software was done for me, so I am quite anxious to know how reliable these haplotypes might be. Potential implications for autoimmune disorders in my family (just started treatment for psoriatic arthritis after 5+ years of odd signs & symptoms - diagnosis based on lab work and X-rays). This and cytochrome P450 imputations are perhaps the most important info that a participant can derive from whole genome results. Can we consider blanket application to all participants??

column12:
My eyes have lightened only slightly since early childhood.  Some of my four children's eyes (all blue or blue with hazel rings or flecks) have lightened through the years (oldest is only 12, youngest not yet four).  My younger sister's blue eyes lightened a lot more than mine, and I've noticed the two of my children with hazel elements in their blue eyes have had their blue lighten up more than the other two.  My nearly-four-year-old daughter has dark blue eyes and looks almost identical to what I did at that age (not just eyes, but overall).  I doubt hers will lighten much; they haven't yet.

My paternal side of family are all blue-eyed, but again, there's a mix of tone.  I think everyone started out with dark or medium blue, and while some reached adulthood with medium to dark blue, others' eyes lightened, to end up with light-medium (no really light/pale blues in our family).  In general, but there may be exceptions, I've observed through the years that the dark-haired (med to dark brown) ones of us have kept a darker spectrum of blue in our eyes, while the lighter-haired (light brown to blonde) members tend to be the ones whose eyes have lightened more.

I have high-degree myopia (-9.50 and -10.00 glasses prescription; -8.00 and -8.50 in contacts).  Some members of my family also have myopia but not nearly as bad as mine.  My sister is the closest, and her contacts prescription is around -3.25. 

I almost forgot. My maternal side of family all have lighter blue eyes or greenish-blue.

Father is African American with dark brown eyes (skin tone like Bill Cosby); mother is Caucasian (German/Welsh- skin tone pinkish/ruddy pale) with light cornflower blue eyes. My only sibling (older brother) looks more biracial (darker skin tone with afro and brown eyes) but strong large build favoring my mother's side. My skin and hair are primarily light beige gold, and my eyes have always been a green-amber hazel. The grey-blue halo presented at about age 42, which is also when I began to get white hair growing in. No eye diseases in my family, although we are all nearsighted. 

My father recently was diagnosed with cataracts, but he is 77. He has outlived all other members of his immediate family, none of which are known to have had any eye diseases. No changes in eyecolor for any of us, although my father's renal disease has caused yellowing to his eyes.

column16: I'm biracial, and even though my features strongly favor my father's side (who is black) My skin, hair, eyecolor, height and weight only resemble some cousins through my paternal grandmother's side. So I basically picked up only the recessive genes in my parents and have no idea why so many showed up in me, whereas my older brother is a more obvious blend of our parents. There is no error in the DNA - this is my actual blood family- but I look like an odd duck because of my small size, light hair skin and eyes.

my eye color is way different than it was when I was little. my eyes were pale blue until I was in around 3rd grade. then they still were kind of grey for years and only in my teens some orange came in. in my twenties they started hazel and gradually got to the muted green they are now at 35. they both still have some orange, more noticeably in my right eye than my left. lots of people still describe my eyes as blue but they don't look blue at all up close.  

my dad has weird grey eyes. I don't know what his looked like when he was young, but my daughter was born with pale blue eyes like me and they darkened as she aged. she's 16 now and her eyes look exactly like my dad's eyes. it's a kind of grey that almost doesnt seem like a real color when you look right at it. kind of a dull steel-ish color that looks different depending on the surroundings. like seeing silverware at the bottom of a creek.

my dad has one eye that rolls sideways, and my daughter has permanent double vision and no depth perception because her eyes both roll away from each other.  the doctor said her brain would delete one eye but it never did. 

my daughter was diagnosed with "retinal migraines" in addition to her eye roll. she was also born pretty strongly farsighted. my dad wears a super strong prescription as well but I don't know his specifics.

my left eye doesn't close all the way and I have to cover it when I sleep, but I think that's from an injury. 

my daughter didn't open her eyes at all for the first six weeks or so after she was born and then she slept with her eyes completely open every night until she was about 15 months old.

my daughter and I definitely see colors differently but I don't know which of us has any colorblindness.

column12: My eyes seem to have changed from solid brown to this ringed design.  I have the bad habit of sleeping with my right eye buried in my pillow and this has distorted my cornea, much to the chagrin of laser surgeons trying to correct it permanently.  My mother's eyes changed from brown to ringed grey, to solid crystal blue, and later in life far sighted.  My father's eyes were always hazel, and he was several times legally blind from near nearsightedness.  The older of my two younger sisters was born with grey eyes which became ringed, and then solid crystal blue.  My youngest sister always had solid crystal blue eyes.  My Paternal Grandmother's eyes changed from my color to crystal blue very late in life.  My paternal grandfather had solid medium brown eyes and nearsightedness.  My Maternal Grandparents had crystal blue eyes.  My Paternal male cousin has medium brown eyes(mild late age farsightedness), and my paternal female cousin has dark brown eyes.
column15: My hair seems to have come from my mother who also had very thin hair strands. My paternal grandmother suffered from what appeared to be the uniform loss of about 2/3 of her hair, and grey hair, perhaps from mercury poisoning. column16: My diet as a child did not include Essential Fatty Acids, such as fish or seeds, or oils.  In my 40's when I tried to supplement with them I became very agitated.  After finishing the a pint of Hemp Oil at about a tablespoon a day, and feeling nervous, my skin changed.  Suddenly many of the scars from my childhood became LIGHT colored on my tanned hands.  On the tip of my pale penis an unseen scar became DARK colored.  After using a tanning bed several times across a couple of weeks during the 80's certain dark scars/moles began to change color and shape appreciably.  None of the scars/moles exposed to constant sunlight or not all year round, during my years on the streets, displayed any changes.  My Paternal Grandfather died of a cancerous mole on his back.  My Paternal Grandmother had "liver spots" all over her hands.  My Maternal Grandfather had a skin condition which made the capillaries in his face pronounced, and my mother developed this in later life.  My Maternal grandmother did not have this. Both me and my father have had "wax pockets" or clogged pores which have filled with so much wax, that they needed to be lanced, or emptied.  My sisters and mother did not have this.  Surgeons have told me that I heal remarkably fast, especially for a person my age (58).

column16:
My overall goal here is to analyze my genomes.  I was born with a High IQ (placed in  the Gifted Program in 2nd Grade) and on course to become a Chemical Engineer or Neurologist until I incurred a TBI the 4th week of my 11th Grade year.  The timing of the Traumatic Brain Injury originally inhibited my Academic goals. However I have worked with the NIH on tDCS and am told that my next Project should be TMS.  I aim to work with Harvard Medical School in a TMS Project, potentially stemming from this PGP.  I well then will make significant research contributions in Neurology and likely return to Medical School to increase my Neurological knowledge.

Then specifically regarding my family's Paternal Genomes of great intelligence (I am a Lot like my father-in looks, speech, etc).  Then my Sister's 10 year old son-Gage is my Father's identical Grandson & my genetic twin (I am not biased, Gage carries many traits of my Father and I and Gage is extremely Smart!!!!)  My nephew is brilliant and 190% of an example of how strong Genes are and carry over!  When Gage was a baby, my Paternal Grandmother  pointed out that Gage behaved as my Dad did when my Dad was a baby!

But enough Aunt Casey ramblings.  It is just really neat to me how strong my Dad's (German descendants) Gene's are.
